Introduction

This exercise uses the data from Friedman (1991)1 to explore how a model deals with noise. Data simulated from a number of informative variables is combined with non-informative variables and models are fit to the data. A useful model would be able to detect the signal and successfully identify the informative variables and filter out the noise. MARS, SVM and KNN models are tested.

This solution uses the tidymodels package to implement the modeling.

Exercise Instructions

Instructions adapted from Kuhn and Johnson (2013)2.

Friedman (1991) introduced several benchmark data sets create by simulation. One of these simulations used the following nonlinear equation to create data:

\[ y = 10 sin(\pi x_1 x_2) + 20(x_3 − 0.5)^2 + 10x_4 + 5x_5 + N(0, \sigma^2) \]

where the \(x\) values are random variables uniformly distributed between \([0, 1]\) (there are also 5 other non-informative variables created in the simulation). The package mlbench contains a function called mlbench.friedman1 that simulates these data. Tune several models on these data. Which models appear to give the best performance? Does MARS select the informative predictors (those named X1 to X5)?

Setup

# Load packages
library(caret)
library(tidyverse)
library(tidymodels)
library(patchwork)
library(mlbench)
library(earth)

# Load my functions:
source("/home/brian/R/dir/Util/bh_functions.R")

# Options:
theme_set(theme_bw())
options(digits = 4)

Data

Training data

Generate the simulated training data:

set.seed(200)
trainingData <- mlbench.friedman1(200, sd = 1)

# We convert the 'x' data from a matrix to a data frame
# One reason is that this will give the columns names.
trainingData$x <- data.frame(trainingData$x)

# Combine the data:
df_train <- cbind(y = trainingData$y, trainingData$x)

Plot the training data using ggplot2 (this is the equivalent of caret::featurePlot()):

df_train %>% 
  pivot_longer(X1:X10, names_to = "sample", values_to = "x") %>% 
  mutate(sample = factor(sample, levels = str_c("X", 1:10), ordered = TRUE)) %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(x, y),
             color = "steelblue", alpha = 0.7) +
  facet_wrap(~sample, nrow = 2) +
  labs(x = "Feature (x)", y = "y")

Test data

Generate test data:

# This creates a list with a vector 'y' and a matrix
# of predictors 'x'. Also simulate a large test set to
# estimate the true error rate with good precision:
testData <- mlbench.friedman1(5000, sd = 1)
testData$x <- data.frame(testData$x)

# Combine the data:
df_test <- cbind(y = testData$y, testData$x)

MARS

Fit a variety of MARS models on the simulated data. We are not using cross-validation in this exercise. Rather, we fit the models on the simulated training data and make predictions on the test data. We will be assessing the models performance using both the test error and by inspecting what variables the models deemed the most important.

Create a grid of parameters to use. We are varying the num_terms and prod_degree parameters:

mars_grid <- expand.grid(num_terms = seq(2,14,by=2), prod_degree = 1:2)

Models specs

Create a list of models, each one with a set of parameters from the grid created above:

mars_mods <- pmap(mars_grid, parsnip::mars)

Fit models

Fit each of the models on the simulated data. (There may be a more compact way of specifying the model parameters as well as the mode and engine in one go. Here I have specified the models and parameters above using pmap(), then I set the mode and engine using map() before passing it on to fit() below):

set.seed(1)
mars_fits <- mars_mods %>% 
  map(function(mod) {
    fit <- mod %>%
      set_engine("earth") %>% 
      set_mode("regression") %>% 
      parsnip::fit(y ~ ., data = df_train) # formula is included here rather than in a separate recipe
  })

Predictions

The test data was simulated above and stored in data frame called df_test. Use this data to make predictions:

preds <- mars_fits %>% 
  map(~predict(., new_data = df_test))

Plot RMSE

# Extract the test RMSE values:
rmse <- map_dbl(preds, ~RMSE(.x$.pred, df_test$y))

# Combine the RMSE values with the grid of model parameters:
mars_grid_rmse <- 
  cbind(mars_grid, rmse) %>%
  mutate(
    prod_degree = factor(prod_degree)
)

# Plot:
mars_grid_rmse %>% 
  ggplot(aes(num_terms, rmse, color = prod_degree)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line() +
  labs(y = "Test RMSE", title = "MARS Test RMSE") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(2, 14, 2)) +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

Best model

Identify the model which gives the lowest test error:

best_params <- mars_grid_rmse %>% 
  arrange(rmse) %>% 
  head(1)
best_params

Create a fresh model with the optimal parameters (I’m not sure that this is the optimal way to do this. I may need to revisit and see if there is a better way to inspect the model that has already been fit):

best_mod <- earth(y ~ ., data = df_train,
                  nprune = best_params$num_terms,
                  degree = as.numeric(best_params$prod_degree))
summary(best_mod)

We can see from the summary that the MARS model has only selected 5 terms and they are the X1 to X5 terms as expected. The other non-informative variables are left unused.

This is also clear from the variable importance measures:

varImp(best_mod)

Plot each predictor versus the outcome using plotmo() (I’m not yet aware of a way to do these plots using ggplot2):

plotmo(best_mod)

Store Test Error

RMSE <- data.frame(
  model = "MARS",
  RMSE = best_params$rmse
)

SVM with Radial Basis Function

Fit a variety of SVM models with radial basis functions on the simulated data.

Data

Use the same data as above.

Grid of parameters

Create a grid of parameters to use:

svm_grid <- expand_grid(cost = 2^c(-2, 0, 2, 8),
                        margin = c(0.01, 0.05, 0.1, 0.5),
                        rbf_sigma = kernlab::sigest(y ~ ., data = df_train, frac = .75))

Models specs

Create a list of models, each one with a set of parameters from the grid created above:

svm_mods <- pmap(svm_grid, parsnip::svm_rbf)

Fit models

Fit each of the models on the simulated data. (There may be a more compact way of specifying the model parameters as well as the mode and engine in one go. Here I have specified the models and parameters above using pmap(), then I set the mode and engine using map() before passing it on to fit() below):

set.seed(1)
svm_fits <- svm_mods %>% 
  map(function(mod) {
    fit <- mod %>%
      set_engine("kernlab") %>% 
      set_mode("regression") %>% 
      parsnip::fit(y ~ ., data = df_train) # formula is included here rather than in a separate recipe
  })

Predictions

The test data was simulated above and stored in data frame called df_test. Use this data to make predictions:

preds <- svm_fits %>% 
  map(~predict(., new_data = df_test))

Plot RMSE

# Extract the test RMSE values:
rmse <- map_dbl(preds, ~RMSE(.x$.pred, df_test$y))

# Combine the RMSE values with the grid of model parameters:
svm_grid_rmse <- cbind(svm_grid, rmse)

# Plot:
svm_grid_rmse %>% 
  mutate(rbf_sigma = factor(round(rbf_sigma, 3)),
         margin = factor(margin)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(cost, rmse, color = rbf_sigma)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line() +
  facet_wrap(~margin, labeller = label_both) +
  labs(y = "Test RMSE", title = "SVM (RBF) Test RMSE") +
  scale_x_continuous(trans = "log2", breaks = 2^c(-2, 0, 2, 8), labels = str_c("2^", c(-2, 0, 2, 8))) +
 # scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(2.1, 2.6, 0.1)) +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

Best model

Identify the model which gives the lowest test error:

best_params <- svm_grid_rmse %>% 
  arrange(rmse) %>% 
  head(1)
best_params

Store Test Error

RMSE <- rbind(
  RMSE,
  c(model = "SVM (RBF)", RMSE = best_params$rmse)
)

KNN

Fit a variety of KNN models on the simulated data.

Data

Use the same data as above.

Models specs

Create a list of models, each one with a set of parameters from the grid created above:

knn_mods <- pmap(knn_grid, parsnip::nearest_neighbor)

Fit models

Fit each of the models on the simulated data. (There may be a more compact way of specifying the model parameters as well as the mode and engine in one go. Here I have specified the models and parameters above using pmap(), then I set the mode and engine using map() before passing it on to fit() below):

RMSE %>%
